      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I understand the challenge. Since the full grid is too big, we need to use a space-optimized DP solution. We can use a single row or a single column to keep our space usage within limits. Here, we'll use the row approach.\n\nLet's declare the num_paths cell to store the current and previous rows respectively:\n\n```python\ndef num_paths(grid):\n    N, M = len(grid), len(grid[0])\n    \n    # Space-optimized DP\n    prev_row = [0] * M\n    curr_row = [0] * M\n    \n    # Initialize the first row\n    curr_row[0] = 1  # Can only come from (N-1, M-1) diagonal\n    for j in range(1, M):\n        if grid[-1][j] != 1:\n            curr_row[j] = curr_row[j-1]\n        if prev_row[-1] != 1:\n            curr_row[j] += prev_row[j-1]\n\n    return curr_row[-1]  # Final count in the current row\n```\n\nTo improve this further, we need to reset the `prev_row` back to 0 every time we encounter a blocked cell in",
